From: mlord@bnr.ca (Mark Lord)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux.help
Subject: Re: Linux keeps using HD when I logged off..
Date: 10 Nov 1993 16:43:39 GMT

In article <5CBnT62Jo_A@rimki.toppoint.de> chrimek@tpki.toppoint.de writes:
>Hello
>
>viznyuk@ohstpy.mps.ohio-state.edu wrote on 02.11.93:
>
>> [...]        .....    What I noted is that even
>> if I logged off, the system pokes at hard disk with
>> about 1 min time interval for some mysterious
..
>You need not fear. What you hear is the update deamon who syncs
>every 30 seconds. update is started by the init process, and you
>can see the start command in /etc/inittab, usually.

Of course, the next logical question is:  wouldn't the first such sync
update everything?  If so, then what is left to be updated every 30 seconds
thereafter?

The answer is probably this (I have not looked closely to verify):
The daemons that continue to run, such as cron, periodically access data
files, without necessarily writing or updating anything.  This by itself
does not cause anything to be written to the device (by sync), but if the
filesystem is mounted r/w, then it tries to keep track of last date/time 
of *access* for each file (a nifty feature), which *does* require that
data be written to the (directory entry on) disk.  Under linux, these writes
are held in buffers, and flushed by sync every 30 seconds.

-- 
mlord@bnr.ca    Mark Lord       BNR Ottawa,Canada       613-763-7482

