From: doolitt@cebaf4.cebaf.gov (Larry Doolittle)
Subject: Re: HELP - Linux counter moral issue
Reply-To: doolitt@cebaf4.cebaf.gov (Larry Doolittle)
Date: Wed, 10 Nov 1993 15:31:34 GMT

In article <2bqs7m$ekp@trane.uninett.no>, hta@uninett.no (Harald T.
Alvestrand) writes:
> 
> Now, this sitemaster seems to have decided to do a mass registration
> by sending in the whole /etc/passwd file at once using a script.
> (It is QUITE plain that the votes were script-generated, but all the
> FROM addresses are different)
> 
> What does the readership of c.o.l.misc think I should do?

I think this sitemaster is overstepping his bounds.
(I say he for simplicity - not trying to be sexist.)
He can put up a "motd" advising his users to take
part, and even provide a script in the default
path to make it easier for his users to register.
For the sitemaster to send in the votes is too much -
besides, how is he supposed to know if his users use
Linux at home or not?

If you still don't have a "friend" counter built,
make a separate copy of the counter for such mass
registrations.  The information would be interesting,
but it would be misleading to merge it without comment
into the original database.

          - Larry Doolittle   doolittle@cebaf.gov

