From: bassman@isoit034.bbn.hp.com (Mr. Bassman)
Subject: Re: HELP - Linux counter moral issue
Date: Wed, 10 Nov 1993 18:16:37 GMT

In article <2bqs7m$ekp@trane.uninett.no>, hta@uninett.no (Harald T. Alvestrand) writes:
|> Hello,
|> I have a "moral" problem regarding the Linux counter.
|> 
|> I have had some exchanges with a particular sitemaster that
|> wanted to register 500 Linux users at that site.
|> 
|> I still haven't implemented "friend counting", so the assumption is
|> that each FROM address gets one vote.
|> 
|> Now, this sitemaster seems to have decided to do a mass registration
|> by sending in the whole /etc/passwd file at once using a script.
|> (It is QUITE plain that the votes were script-generated, but all the
|> FROM addresses are different)
|> 
|> This will have the interesting effect of sending this country to
|> the head of the class where Linux usage is concerned - FAR ahead
|> of everybody else.
|> 
|> Now, I can do several things:
|> 
|> - Ignore it, and let the votes be counted
|> - Delete all votes from this site, keeping the statistics as they are,
|>   but not gathering the information
|> - Recommending that other Linux admins do a "mass registration" of their
|>   users, ensuring a certain "evenness" to the count.

        It's no secret that statitics are very easily manipulated to show
numerous results from the same info (if you want a good example, take a look
at the opinion polls preceding any governmental election).

        To do the first option would (as I see it) count as inadvertant
manipulation of statistics. The post suggests that the country concerned is
not as far ahead as the new results would put it.

        The second option seems a little unfair. I think that every linux user
has the right to be counted (ok - assuming they wish to be). I dare say that
some of them are now proud that they can actually do something worthwhile with
their PC's, and would probably be somewhat put out if their votes were ignored.

        The third option is, in my opinion, the best by far. It's fair to all,
and gives the best reflection of the number of users. There would have to be
some conditions enforced for allowing people to do this, to avoid the faking
of figures. God only knows why anyone would want to fake results, and he didn't
tell me last time I spoke to him. Sorry. It might be an idea to ask for an
IP address or nodename etc, from sys admins so that the new info can fit in
with what's current, instead of just having me mail you saying we've got 10000
linux boxes here. (In fact, we only have two.)

        Well, that's what I think...

Mr. Bassman
Hewlett-Packard, Boeblingen, Germany
bassman@hpbbi30.bbn.com

